University.

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:34.400
Cristina Rivera Garza
was born in Matamoros,

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:37.030
Tamaulipas, Mexico in 1964.

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:39.740
She's the author of six
novels, three collections

00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:42.560
of short stories, five
collections of poetry

00:08:42.560 --> 00:08:44.490
and three non-fiction books.

00:08:44.490 --> 00:08:48.280
Her books have been translated
to multiple languages,

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:52.660
including English, French,
Italian, Portuguese and Korean.

00:08:52.660 --> 00:08:56.800
She has a PhD from the
University of Houston,

00:08:56.800 --> 00:08:59.590
at her dissertation from
the departure point for both

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:02.130
"Nadie me verá llorar", one
of her most golden novels,

00:09:02.130 --> 00:09:05.740
and the historical non-fiction
book "La Castañeda",

00:09:05.740 --> 00:09:08.840
on Mexico's most
infamous mental hospital.

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:10.500
After a few years
at the University

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:12.850
of California San Diego,
she's now a professor

00:09:12.850 --> 00:09:15.380
of Hispanic studies of
the University of Houston,

00:09:15.380 --> 00:09:17.050
where she has been spearheading
the first PhD program

00:09:17.050 --> 00:09:20.260
in creative writing and Spanish.

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:23.180
The recipient of the
Roger Caillois Award

00:09:23.180 --> 00:09:26.670
for Latin American literature,
as well as the Ana Serves Prize,

00:09:26.670 --> 00:09:30.420
she's the only author who was
won the International Sor Juana

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:34.400
de la Cruz prize twice,
in 2001 for her novel

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:37.050
"Nadie me verá llorar",
translated into English

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:40.360
by Andrew Hurley as "No one
will see me cry", and again,

00:09:40.360 --> 00:09:44.700
in 2009 for her novel
"La muerte me da".

00:09:44.700 --> 00:09:48.530
Suzanne Jill Levine has received
many honors for her translations

00:09:48.530 --> 00:09:50.140
of Latin American literature.

00:09:50.140 --> 00:09:53.930
She's the author of "Manuel Puig
and The Spider Woman, his life

00:09:53.930 --> 00:09:56.680
and fictions", and
"The subversive scribe,

00:09:56.680 --> 00:09:59.170
translating Latin
American fiction".

00:09:59.170 --> 00:10:00.800
Her editions include
the "Penguin

00:10:00.800 --> 00:10:02.140
"paper bag classic series

00:10:02.140 --> 00:10:06.830
of Jorge Luis Borge's
essays and poetry.

00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:10.280
Aviva Kana is a PhD candidate
in Hispanic literature

00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:12.870
at the University of
California Santa Barbara.

00:10:12.870 --> 00:10:15.770
Her work focuses on Latin
American literature, gender,

00:10:15.770 --> 00:10:18.640
translation, and
applied linguistics.

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:21.440
Her translations have been
published in "Review, Literature

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:24.310
and Arts of the Americas",
"PEN America",

00:10:24.310 --> 00:10:28.100
"Latin American literature
today" and fiction.

00:10:28.100 --> 00:10:30.200
And finally, Manuel
Cuellar, our moderator,

00:10:30.200 --> 00:10:32.410
he's an assistant
professor of Spanish

00:10:32.410 --> 00:10:34.270
and Latin American
literatures and cultures

00:10:34.270 --> 00:10:36.740
at the George Washington
University.

00:10:36.740 --> 00:10:40.470
His research and teaching
focuses on Mexican literary

00:10:40.470 --> 00:10:42.850
and cultural studies,
with an emphasis

00:10:42.850 --> 00:10:45.470
on race, gender and sexuality.

00:10:45.470 --> 00:10:47.940
His current book
manuscript "Assemblages

00:10:47.940 --> 00:10:50.480
of a festive nation,
queer embodiments

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:53.790
and dancing histories of
Mexico" studies dancing bodies

00:10:53.790 --> 00:10:57.530
and public spaces, in order to
privilege movement as a means

00:10:57.530 --> 00:11:00.690
to examine questions
of citizen formation

00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:02.500
and national belonging.

